---
import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import Link from '../../components/Link.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/TableOfContents.astro';
const title = 'Decal Shader - Cities Skylines Modding';
import { Picture } from 'astro:assets';
import { images } from '../../data/imageImports.js';
---

<MainLayout title={title}>
	<TableOfContents />
	<section class="py-12 text-lg sm:ml-64 xl:mr-64 text-hit-gray-500">
		<h1 id="overview" class="pb-8 text-4xl font-bold border-b-4 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400">
			Decal Shader
		</h1>
		<div class="content">
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="about">
				About
			</h2>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						The decal shader can be used to create decal props of any size, and it's also possible to tile
						the decal texture.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalmud.jpeg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.decalmud.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.decalmud}
							alt="Example mud decals"
							class="w-full h-auto"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Example mud decals.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="mesh">
				Mesh
			</h2>
			<p class="mt-4">
				It's not required to make your own mesh, you can download the premade decal mesh, which is ready to be
				used with the decal script which will do the rest.
			</p>
			<div class="mt-4 content-download">
				<Link
					classes=""
					href="https://drive.google.com/open?id=1hr6l0HO76g3K7tV3At_Brx29-EHxDVAQ"
					text="Download"
					theme="downloadbutton"
				/>
			</div>
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="textures">
				Textures
			</h2>
			<p class="mt-4">These determine the color and material properties of your decal.</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="diffuse">
				Diffuse
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>The main color and texture of your asset.</p><p class="mt-4">
						It will look very bright, contrasty, and saturated in the game, so make sure to reduce the
						saturation and limit the brightest parts to a medium/light gray below 140 RGB.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import a diffuse map, it will default to white.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/shader/decal/decaldiff.jpeg" target="_blank">
							<Picture
								width={images.decaldiff.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.decaldiff}
								alt="Example diffuse texture for a mud decal"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example diffuse texture for a mud decal.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/color_reference.png" target="_blank">
							<Picture
								width={images.color_guidelines.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.color_guidelines}
								alt="Color guidelines"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Color guidelines.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="alpha">
				Alpha
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						Transparency, white means opaque or visible, black means transparent or invisible. Gray values
						will be semi-transparent.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import an alpha map, it will default to white - fully visible.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalalpha.jpeg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.decalalpha.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.decalalpha}
							alt="Example alpha texture for a mud decal"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Example alpha texture for a mud decal.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="color">
				Color
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Determines which parts will be affected by color variations. White means fully affected and black means
				not at all.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The diffuse will get multiplied by the color variation, that means the resulting color will look darker
				than the original diffuse.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				If you don't import a color map, it will default to full color, but the "use color variations" setting
				must be enabled for the colors to appear.
			</p>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="illumination"
			>
				Illumination
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Allows for diffuse contribution illumination. Black means no illumination and white means the brightest
				possible illumination. For decals, the illumination is not very noticeable.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">If you don't import an illumination map, it will default to no illumination.</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="specular">
				Specular
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						Reflectivity, black means no reflection and white means max reflection. As opposed to other
						types of assets, decals don't display a specular highlight from the sun, they only display the
						environment cubemap reflection.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import a specular map, it will default to no specularity.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalspec.jpeg" target="_blank">
							<Picture
								width={images.decalspec.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.decalspec}
								alt="Example specular map for a mud decal"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example specular map for a mud decal.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalspec2.jpeg" target="_blank">
							<Picture
								width={images.decalspec2.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.decalspec2}
								alt="Transitions between different specular values produce artifacts on the normal map"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">
							Transitions between different specular values produce artifacts on the normal map and vice
							versa, even if a normal map is not imported.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="normal">
				Normal
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The normal map only affects the reflective parts of decals, therefore it's often not useful.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Read more about normal maps in the <Link
					classes=""
					href="/asset/prop/#normal"
					text="prop asset creation article"
					theme="internallink"
				/>.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">If you don't import a normal map, it will default to a flat normal map - no bump.</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="format">
				Format
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">Use a lossless format like .PNG.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The game supports other formats as well, but there is no reason to use another one, it doesn't matter
				how much your texture is compressed or even if it's completely solid or complicated, the game will
				convert it to a DXT format, so the final size won't be affected by anything other than resolution.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Make sure the texture is 8 bits/channel because a 16 bits/channel image can't be imported. Do not use
				the "Smaller File (8-bit)" feature in the Photoshop Export As window, as that creates an indexed color
				image, not an 8 bits/channel one.
			</p>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="resolution"
			>
				Resolution
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">All imported main textures must be the same resolution.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Powers of 2 is a standard practice in 3D graphics, which means resolutions such as 1024x1024, 1024x512,
				256x512, 2048x128 etc. It is recommended to stick to this standard, otherwise, your texture may be
				corrupted by compression, which may be more visible at longer distances or grazing angles. The smallest
				allowed resolution is 32x32.
			</p>
			<div class="flex items-start justify-start gap-2 mt-6">
				<svg
					class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 text-orange"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path
						d="M12 9v3.75m-9.303 3.376c-.866 1.5.217 3.374 1.948 3.374h14.71c1.73 0 2.813-1.874 1.948-3.374L13.949 3.378c-.866-1.5-3.032-1.5-3.898 0L2.697 16.126zM12 15.75h.007v.008H12v-.008z"
						stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						Make sure texture quality is set to high in the game's graphics settings. otherwise, your
						imported textures will be downscaled to a lower resolution.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="import">
				Import
			</h2>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="naming">
				Naming
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">The mesh can have any name.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The textures must have the same name as the mesh, but with the texture type identifier after it, so the
				result will be names like meshname_d.png, meshname_a.png etc.
			</p>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="import-folder"
			>
				Import Folder
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>You should place the mesh and texture files in the import folder located here:</p><p
						class="mt-4"
					>
						%LocalAppData%\Colossal Order\Cities_Skylines\Addons\Import
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						The AppData folder is hidden by default, you can access it by copying and pasting the path into
						the file explorer, or pressing <span class="key">Windows + R</span> and typing in appdata.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalnaming.jpeg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.decalnaming.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.decalnaming}
							alt="Files ready for import"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Files ready for import.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="template">
				Template
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The template you choose doesn't matter, as the script will change all the relevant values.
			</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="import-1">
				Import
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3"><p>No scaling or rotation is necessary for the premade mesh.</p></div>
				<div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalimport.jpeg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.decalimport.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.decalimport}
							alt="Importing the mesh in asset importer"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Importing the mesh in asset importer.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="flex items-start justify-start gap-2 mt-6">
				<svg
					class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 text-orange"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path
						d="M12 9v3.75m-9.303 3.376c-.866 1.5.217 3.374 1.948 3.374h14.71c1.73 0 2.813-1.874 1.948-3.374L13.949 3.378c-.866-1.5-3.032-1.5-3.898 0L2.697 16.126zM12 15.75h.007v.008H12v-.008z"
						stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						If you get an unsupported color error, one of your textures might be a 16 bits/channel file, you
						need to change it to 8 bits/channel, in Photoshop: Image &gt; Mode &gt; 8 Bits/Channel.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="Script">
				Script
			</h2>
			<p class="mt-4">
				To change the shader of your prop to decal and set the size of your decal, you need to run <Link
					classes=""
					href="https://gist.github.com/ronyx69/ffff7459be346bc807b72b99713bbf9f"
					text="this script"
					theme="externallink"
				/> using the <Link
					classes=""
					href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=450877484"
					text="ModTools"
					theme="externallink"
				/> console <span class="key">F7</span>.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">The result will be instantly visible and it's fine to run the script multiple times.</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="variables">
				Variables
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">At the top of the script, you can change some variables.</p>
			<h4 class="pb-4 mt-8 text-xl font-medium border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-950 lg:mt-12" id="size">
				Size
			</h4>
			<p class="mt-4">
				This defines the width and length of your decal in meters, the texture width and height will be
				stretched to match this size.
			</p>
			<h4 class="pb-4 mt-8 text-xl font-medium border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-950 lg:mt-12" id="tile">
				Tile
			</h4>
			<p class="mt-4">
				This allows to tile the texture multiple times in width and length directions. This is usually left at
				1.
			</p>
			<h4
				class="pb-4 mt-8 text-xl font-medium border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-950 lg:mt-12"
				id="slope-tolerance"
			>
				Slope Tolerance
			</h4>
			<p class="mt-4">
				This defines the height of the decal box mesh, which determines the amount of sloped terrain the decal
				will be able to handle, once the terrain slope exceeds this value, the decal will begin fading out at
				the top and bottom.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">When the camera enters the decal box mesh, the decal will not be visible.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				If you leave this as a negative value, the script will automatically calculate a reasonable value.
			</p>
			<h2
				class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400"
				id="editor-advanced"
			>
				Editor Advanced
			</h2>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						Various things can be changed with the use of <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=450877484"
							text="ModTools"
							theme="externallink"
						/> scene explorer <span class="key">Ctrl+E</span> or running scripts in the console <span
							class="key">F7</span
						>, or specific mods.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalmodtools.jpeg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.decalmodtools.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.decalmodtools}
							alt="ModTools scene explorer and console"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">ModTools scene explorer and console.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="ui-category"
			>
				UI Priority
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				UIPriority determines item order in the menu. It can be changed <Link
					classes=""
					href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=466485089"
					text="Asset UI Priority Changer by Snow_Cat"
					theme="externallink"
				/> or <Link
					classes=""
					href="https://gist.github.com/ronyx69/60e9297695ff983b655b05b21f0407e5"
					text="a script"
					theme="externallink"
				/>.
			</p>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="variations"
			>
				Variations
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						You can add multiple prop assets to your prop as variations using a probability value. The
						probability is a percentage out of 100, but the main prop has no probability so it gets whatever
						is left over, so if you have two variations with a 25% probability each, the main prop will get
						a 50% probability. The variations will be embedded into the main prop, but also show up as
						separate props in the menu.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						Run <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://gist.github.com/ronyx69/8071d41a135cdb5d1f1f0627b5806b6d"
							text="this script"
							theme="externallink"
						/> using the <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=450877484"
							text="ModTools"
							theme="externallink"
						/> console <span class="key">F7</span> to set the variation amount, and also calculate equal
						probability automatically.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalvariations.jpeg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.decalvariations.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.decalvariations}
							alt="Prop variations menu in the asset editor"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Prop variations menu in the asset editor.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="save">
				Save
			</h2>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="filename">
				Filename
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						The filename input is on the bottom right, this is what the actual file will be called. It's not
						recommended to use spaces, dots, or special symbols.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/shader/decal/decalsave.jpeg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.decalsave.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.decalsave}
							alt="Save asset window"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Save asset window.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="asset-name"
			>
				Asset Name
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">The asset name visible ingame, the name people should search for.</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="images">
				Images
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">There are 2 different folders you can open by clicking the folder icons:</p>
			<h4
				class="pb-4 mt-8 text-xl font-medium border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-950 lg:mt-12"
				id="snapshot"
			>
				Snapshot
			</h4>
			<p class="mt-4">
				On the snapshot image, bottom right corner. Use this one to replace the snapshot, you can replace it
				with a 1x1 px image to save on the asset file size. This image will only be visible in the content
				manager. It will also default as the Steam preview image, but you can change that separately when
				publishing.
			</p>
			<h4
				class="pb-4 mt-8 text-xl font-medium border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-950 lg:mt-12"
				id="thumbnail-tooltip"
			>
				Thumbnail &amp; Tooltip
			</h4>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Below thumbnail, on the right side. Use this one to change the thumbnail (109x100) and tooltip (492x147)
